User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 14 responses, 4 participants reported they currently use MRI for research. The majority of respondents, 71%, indicated a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

Here’s a summary of the research areas mentioned in the survey responses:

  • Cognitive Neuroscience: This is the most prominent area, with multiple respondents specifically mentioning it. Sub-specialties include music cognition, predictive processing, and the use of non-invasive brain stimulation.
  • Neuroscience: A general area with some respondents specifying affective, social and political, and others focusing on brain injury in sport.
  • Mental Health: This area is represented by responses mentioning sexual health, mental disorders/psychotherapy (including rTMS), and clinical psychology.
  • Other Areas: Additional areas mentioned are Multiple Sclerosis, Body Image, Qualitative Research, and Cognevrp.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

The survey responses indicate that increased access to MRI would significantly enhance and expand research in several key areas:

  • Understanding Brain Function: Respondents highlighted the potential to investigate brain function in areas such as sexual arousal and dysfunction, decision-making related to partner attraction and sexual preferences, memory, and cognitive changes across the lifespan.
  • Improving Research Quality and Scope: Better MRI access would enable researchers to collect essential data beyond clinical trials, enhance the quality of fMRI research, and increase participant sample sizes.
  • Investigating Neurological Mechanisms: Researchers mentioned using MRI to study the mechanisms underlying non-invasive brain stimulation, both generally and as a treatment for clinical disorders.
  • Broader Data Collection and Reproducibility: MRI’s widespread use allows for testing the reproducibility of findings across different populations, strengthening research validity.
  • Potential for Patient Access: Some researchers indicated that access could benefit research participants who may want to have MRI imaging as a result of the work.

One respondent specifically emphasized the importance of an organizational model that allows trained scientists to manage the scanner, independent of monetary concerns.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Several survey responses highlight the challenge of securing additional resources for MRI research, particularly in light of existing financial commitments to scanner upgrades within specific institutions, such as IVS at UIO. This suggests a need for creative funding solutions and collaborative efforts to leverage existing infrastructure effectively, perhaps through shared access programs or prioritized resource allocation based on research impact.

Conclusion

The results from this survey will be used to create a compelling and data-driven application for the national grant scheme. The insights gathered will help us to clearly articulate the needs of the research community and build a strong case for investment in MRI infrastructure.
